opened_prs.title: Interoperable address spec
opened_prs.body:
I believe this is at a state where we can start a discussion. It is by no means final.

While resolver with id 3 is a good stopgap solution in my opinion, I believe we should iterate on this to:
- define another interface which uses CAIP-10 addresses in the short term, and a resolver using it
- define another resolver which resorts to something like ERC-7785 for chain identification in the longer term, to do away with the usage of centralized lists.

There are several lower-level items where I would greatly appreciate your ideas and feedback, see my own comments in the diff

closed_prs.title: Docs: Atomic Swaps with Local Verification
closed_prs.body: Introduces a permissionless and trustless cross-chain asset transfer mechanism using Atomic Swaps, PreHTLCs, and local verification. This approach ensures fast settlement times without relying on cross-chain messaging protocols or third-party trust.

opened_issues.title: [Task] Chain-Specific Addresses
opened_issues.body:
## Overview
Track the full process for "Chain-Specific Addresses" from initial research to finalizing the ERC. This includes gathering and comparing current efforts, digesting feedback, creating user stories, and ultimately drafting and finalizing the ERC.

## Objectives
- [x] #19 
- [ ] #20 
- [ ] #21 
- [ ] #22 
- [ ] #23 

## Details
- **Background:**  
  Chain-specific addresses are critical for interoperability. We need to consolidate existing efforts, analyze them, and ensure community feedback informs the requirements and user stories.
  
- **Requirements:**  
  - Research and compile current efforts on chain-specific addresses.
  - Organize a review session to digest findings and gather feedback.
  - Develop detailed user stories that capture the desired functionality and outcomes.
  - Draft an ERC based on these insights.
  - Iterate the draft ERC based on further feedback until a final version is agreed upon.

- **Acceptance Criteria:**  
  - Comprehensive documentation of current efforts and comparison is available.
  - Community feedback is documented and reflected in user stories.
  - A draft ERC is published for review.
  - A final ERC is approved and merged.

## Dependencies
- Coordination with team and community.
- Access to data and reports on current chain-specific address efforts.
- Review availability and proactive feedback loops.

## Additional Notes
- Ensure all documentation is maintained in the repository for transparency.
- Use standard templates and formats to ensure consistency.
- Regular updates and clear communication will be essential throughout this process.

opened_issues.title: [Task] Compare efforts
opened_issues.body:
## Overview
Create one document per category (3 total) that aggregates current interop efforts and compares them both against each other and against the defined [PROPERTIES](https://github.com/ethereum/L2-interop/PROPERTIES.md)

## Objectives
- [x] **Objective 1:** Compare current efforts for Chain-Specific Addresses.
- [ ] **Objective 2:** Compare current efforts for Message Passing.
- [ ] **Objective 3:** Compare current efforts for Intents.
- [ ] **Objective 4:** Evaluate, on each respective document, the efforts against the defined [PROPERTIES](https://github.com/ethereum/L2-interop/PROPERTIES.md).

## Details
- **Background:** We need to understand not only what each team is doing within a category but also how these efforts stack up against our defined PROPERTIES for success.
- **Requirements:** 
  - Create a markdown document for each category.
  - For each document, list the current efforts, compare them against each other, and evaluate how well they meet the PROPERTIES.
- **Acceptance Criteria:** 
  - All three documents are complete.
  - Each document includes clear comparisons between efforts and against the PROPERTIES.
  - Documents are verified by the respective teams and merged into the repo.

## Dependencies
- Coordinate with each team lead for accurate data and property definitions.
- Ensure alignment with existing documentation formats.

## Deliverables
- Three markdown documents (one per category) that aggregate and compare current interop efforts against one another and against the PROPERTIES.

## Additional Notes
- Follow our standard documentation format.
- Ensure the documents are clear, concise, and easy to update.

wartime_milady_ceo_summary: - **Weekly Summary:** This week's activity in the repository primarily focused on documentation and planning for interoperability features, with a significant emphasis on enhancing cross-chain interactions. The tone of the PRs and issues suggests a strategic and forward-thinking approach, aiming to lay down foundational work for future development. The closed PR introduced a novel mechanism for cross-chain asset transfers, while the open issues are centered around organizing and formalizing interoperability standards.

- **PR #16 - Atomic Swaps with Local Verification:** A major development was the closure of PR #16, which introduced a permissionless and trustless cross-chain asset transfer mechanism using Atomic Swaps, PreHTLCs, and local verification. This innovative approach offers fast settlement times without the need for cross-chain messaging protocols
